      Poly
   =20
 =20
Yesterday =E2=80=9C hackers perpetrated what is likely the biggest theft ev=
er in the world of decentralized finance, stealing about $600 million in cr=
yptocurrency from a protocol known as PolyNetwork that lets users swap toke=
ns across multiple blockchains.=E2=80=9D There was not much that PolyNetwor=
k could do except ask the hacker nicely to give the money back. So that=E2=
=80=99s what it did. Poly Network tweeted a picture of a plaintive letter a=
ddressed =E2=80=9CDear Hacker.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWe want to establish commu=
nication with you and urge you to return the hacked assets,=E2=80=9D it say=
s. =E2=80=9CThe money you stole are from tens of thousands of crypto commun=
ity members, hence the people. You should talk to us to work out a solution=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0And, uh, that maybe worked?Incredibly, hackers appear to ha=
ve listened. Around $2m has been returned so far. The apparent hackers embe=
dded the message "READY TO RETURN THE FUND!" in an ethereum transaction on =
Thursday morning. A second message embedded in a transaction read: "IT'S AL=
READY A LEGEND TO WIN SO MUCH FORTUNE. IT WILL BE AN ETERNAL LEGEND TO SAVE=
 THE WORLD. I MADE THE DECISION, NO MORE DAO". The return is=C2=A0still in =
progress=C2=A0and can be monitored=C2=A0on the blockchain.From a bit=C2=A0l=
ater this morning:The attacker of the $611 million Poly Network exploit has=
 started returning the stolen crypto assets, less than a day after their ID=
 information was reportedly obtained by blockchain security firm Slowmist. =
=C2=A0They have now sent back $256 million in tokens out of the haul.That=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=A6=C2=A0nice? Crypto is weird because it combines an etho=
s of absolute libertarianism =E2=80=94=C2=A0a focus on incentive design, a =
belief in the inevitable rightness of market outcomes, a sense of personal =
responsibility for any mistakes =E2=80=94=C2=A0with an ethos of collaborati=
ve open-source software development.So on the one hand people build smart c=
ontracts and put hundreds of millions of dollars in them and put the source=
 code online, and then other people find bugs in those contracts and exploi=
t them ruthlessly to steal all the money, and then still other people are l=
ike =E2=80=9Cyep right that=E2=80=99s how it=E2=80=99s supposed to work, sh=
ould have checked the code more carefully, it=E2=80=99s your fault your mon=
ey got stolen.=E2=80=9D One of the first big DeFi-ish hacks  was =E2=80=9Ct=
he DAO=E2=80=9D back in 2016, and when hackers stole $60 million of Ether f=
rom that smart contract, the hackers had a lot of defenders. =E2=80=9CThere=
 is no real legal difference between a feature and an exploit,=E2=80=9D one=
 commenter wrote. If the code of a smart contract allows someone to take mo=
ney out, then they=E2=80=99re allowed to take money out; there is no standa=
rd of legality or morality outside of the code itself.[1]=C2=A0On the other=
 hand lots of people got into the crypto project because they are nice and =
working together to build a better world, not just grab money for themselve=
s, and sometimes when they take a bunch of money out they are like =E2=80=
=9Cwell that was fun but we=E2=80=99re not monsters=E2=80=9D and give it ba=
ck.Or not, I don=E2=80=99t know, maybe they=E2=80=99ll change their minds a=
gain. Still there is some chance this will turn out to be a hilariously hea=
rtwarming story.If you want to read more about how the hack worked, the can=
onical explanations appear to be here and here, but at a high level it is s=
traightforward enough: There was a bug in Poly Network=E2=80=99s code that =
let the hackers send money to themselves, so they did. If you want to read =
a non-altruistic, possibly more realistic explanation of why they=E2=80=99r=
e returning the money, here=E2=80=99s this:=E2=80=9CI think this demonstrat=
es that even if you can steal cryptoassets, laundering them and cashing out=
 is extremely difficult, due to the transparency of the blockchain and the =
use of blockchain analytics,=E2=80=9D Tom Robinson, chief scientist of bloc=
kchain analytics firm Elliptic, said via email.=E2=80=9CIn this case the ha=
cker concluded that the safest option was just to return the stolen assets.=
=E2=80=9DOnce the hackers stole the money, they began to send it to various=
 other cryptocurrency addresses. Researchers at security company SlowMist s=
aid a total of more than $610 million worth of cryptocurrency was transferr=
ed to three addresses.SlowMist said in a tweet that its researchers had =E2=
=80=9Cgrasped the attacker=E2=80=99s mailbox, IP, and device fingerprints=
=E2=80=9D and are =E2=80=9Ctracking possible identity clues related to the =
Poly Network attacker.=E2=80=9DIt is not exactly the sort of regulation and=
 reversibility that you get in the traditional financial system, but it is =
maybe a sort of distributed crowdsourced version of that. Not =E2=80=9Cif y=
ou steal money the bank will reverse the transaction and the government wil=
l come after you,=E2=80=9D but maybe =E2=80=9Cif you steal money=C2=A0someo=
ne will reverse the transaction and someone will come after you.=E2=80=9DAn=
d here is Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Joe Weisenthal arguing that stablecoin issue=
rs have some of that regulatory function.=C2=A0Also this (from yesterday) i=
s cute:Tether froze more than $30 million in response to the hack =E2=80=A6=
.About an hour following Poly Network=E2=80=99s announcement of the hack, t=
he perpetrator attempted to move stolen assets through the Ethereum address=
 into Curve.fi, but the transaction was blocked. The hackers continued tryi=
ng for about 20-30 minutes before an anonymous user sent the hackers a mess=
age on the blockchain that USD Tether had been blocked.=C2=A0The user told =
the hackers to try depositing the stolen tokens without Tether, which the h=
ackers did successfully and they deposited all the addresses into Curve. Th=
e hackers then sent the anonymous user about $45,000 worth of ethereum for =
their help.=C2=A0If you see someone in a ski mask outside of a bank stuffin=
g bags with dollar signs on them into a getaway car, and you notice that th=
ey have dropped some of the bags in their haste to stuff them into the car,=
 it is only polite to stop and help them pick up the bags.[2] And then it i=
s only polite for them to give you one of the bags with dollar signs on the=
m as a thank-you for your help. Everyone in Crypto Town is so friendly, but=
 also so many of them are bank robbers.
 =20
   =20
      Speaking of stablecoins
   =20
 =20
Here is the basic story of stablecoins. It is very useful, for people who t=
rade crypto, to have a cryptocurrency worth $1. In many respects you live y=
our life denominated in dollars, so you want a supply of dollars (as oppose=
d to volatile assets like Bitcoin, etc.). But in many other respects you li=
ve your life=C2=A0on the blockchain, so you want your money to be on the bl=
ockchain (as opposed to in a bank account in the U.S. payments system). A c=
ryptocurrency worth a dollar solves both these problems: It is worth a doll=
ar, but it can be traded on the blockchain, transferred between crypto exch=
anges, held in a crypto wallet, and generally used as a cryptocurrency with=
out interacting with the U.S. banking system.But how do you get a cryptocur=
rency worth exactly $1? There are  some bad ways, but there=E2=80=99s also =
a=C2=A0good simple way, which is that someone=C2=A0else=C2=A0interacts with=
 the banking system =E2=80=94=C2=A0by keeping dollars in the bank =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0and issues a crypto token backed by those dollars, a =E2=80=9Cblockch=
ain depositary receipt=E2=80=9D on some dollars in the bank. You give them =
a dollar, they give you back the token, and they put the dollar in the bank=
; you use the token on the blockchain as a cryptocurrency; later, if you wa=
nt, you give them back the token and they give you back the dollar. That cr=
ypto token =E2=80=94=C2=A0a stablecoin =E2=80=94=C2=A0is worth a dollar, so=
 long as (1) you trust that person to actually keep the money in the bank a=
nd (2) you trust the legal, contractual, personal, etc. arrangements in whi=
ch they promise to exchange the tokens back for dollars.This is the good si=
mple way, but problems can creep in. One set of problems has to do with ban=
ks. Three problems with banks are:=09They  don=E2=80=99t really want deposi=
ts right now: Interest rates are low and bank capital requirements are cons=
training, so banks are not exactly competing fiercely to get billions of do=
llars of deposits.=09They especially don=E2=80=99t want deposits from crypt=
o companies, because crypto raises all sorts of miscellaneous legal risks.=
=09The bank might lose your money. U.S. deposit-insurance limits aren=E2=80=
=99t that high. Banks do not go bust all that often and take depositor mone=
y with them, but it=E2=80=99s a thing you might worry about; you might want=
 to diversify your holdings beyond one giant bank account.I want to emphasi=
ze the third problem in particular. Money-market funds are  in many ways a =
lot like (more regulated versions of) stablecoins, and they don=E2=80=99t j=
ust put all their money in bank accounts. In part because they want to earn=
 a bit more yield, but also because=C2=A0as a risk management decision=C2=
=A0putting all your money in an account with one bank has some drawbacks.An=
other set of problems has to do with the people running the stablecoin, whi=
ch is, you know, if you work in a lightly-to-not-at-all-regulated business =
and have billions of dollars of customer money just sitting there in a bank=
 account, there are certain temptations. Three major temptations are:=09You=
 might stretch for yield. The way you make money as a stablecoin operator i=
s pretty much that the money you put in the bank earns interest, while you =
do not pay any interest to your customers (the people holding the tokens). =
This is a pleasant business to be in, but it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0great=C2=A0=
when bank accounts pay very little (or even negative) interest. If you inve=
sted the money in something else =E2=80=94=C2=A0high-yield bonds, say =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0you would get more interest, and you=E2=80=99d get to keep it. =
If the things you invest in lose value then, oops, your customers will be m=
ad.=09You might   lend the money to your friends. Some stablecoins are affi=
liated with crypto exchanges or other crypto-y businesses. Those businesses=
 sometimes need financing. The stablecoin has a huge pot of money. The affi=
liated business might come to the stablecoin and say =E2=80=9Chey, lend us =
the money, we=E2=80=99ll pay it back with interest, we promise.=E2=80=9D An=
d then the stablecoin will do that, because the people running the stableco=
in and the people running the affiliated business are colleagues, or friend=
s, or sometimes the same exact people. And then if the affiliated business =
loses money then, oops, your=C2=A0customers will be mad.=09You could just s=
teal the money, why not.The combination of all of these factors means that =
it would honestly be kind of surprising for a stablecoin to actually be bac=
ked by a pot of money in a bank account. On the other hand, =E2=80=9Cwe are=
 backed by a bunch of dollars in a bank account=E2=80=9D is a very pleasant=
 thing for a stablecoin to=C2=A0say, because it sounds so simple and so saf=
e. And, you know, lightly-to-not-at-all-regulated business. So =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0uh ... you could just say it? Anyway:For months, a visitor to the websit=
e of Coinbase Global Inc., the largest U.S. cryptocurrency exchange, would =
see that the company offered a stablecoin called USD Coin with a simple pre=
mise: For every dollar offered to investors, there was $1 =E2=80=9Cin a ban=
k account=E2=80=9D to back it.That promise was important for the stablecoin=
, which unlike Bitcoin has a set price and can be redeemed by users for reg=
ular currency. It helped USD Coin grow to be the world=E2=80=99s second-lar=
gest stablecoin, with $28 billion in assets.=C2=A0But when Circle Internet =
Financial Inc., Coinbase=E2=80=99s partner in offering the coin, disclosed =
USD Coin=E2=80=99s assets for the first time last month, it turns out the p=
romise wasn=E2=80=99t true.According to a disclosure in July, the assets ac=
tually include commercial paper, corporate bonds and other assets that coul=
d experience losses and are less liquid if customers ever tried to redeem t=
he stablecoin en masse.Oopsie! The disclosure says that Circle has 61% of i=
ts assets in =E2=80=9Ccash and cash equivalents,=E2=80=9D though that inclu=
des not just bank accounts but also government money market funds and =E2=
=80=9Csecurities with an original maturity less than or equal to 90 days.=
=E2=80=9D The rest includes certificates of deposit, U.S. Treasuries, comme=
rcial paper and corporate bonds. It is not obviously a super-aggressive mix=
 or anything, and you can see where they=E2=80=99re coming from. But it is =
not money in a bank account.=C2=A0We have talked about this problem before =
with Tether, the biggest stablecoin, which got in trouble for=C2=A0doing  h=
ilarious related-party loans while still pretending that it was backed by c=
ash in bank accounts. As part of its settlement for that, it had to stop pr=
etending that it was backed by cash in bank accounts, and now it discloses =
its asset mix, though in a way that  still makes people very nervous. It=E2=
=80=99s slowly trying to do better:Tether Holdings Ltd. released the most d=
etailed version yet of the assets backing its widely used digital currency,=
 seeking to address regulatory concerns that it hasn=E2=80=99t previously d=
isclosed enough about the currency=E2=80=99s underpinnings. ...Roughly half=
 of Tether=E2=80=99s $62.8 billion in assets were held in commercial paper =
and certificates of deposit, according to a report the company published Mo=
nday. It detailed for the first time the credit ratings of these notes, say=
ing that about 93% of them were rated A-2 or higher, indicating an investme=
nt-grade, short-term rating. ...The report said that 24% of its assets were=
 in Treasury bills=E2=80=94considered among the safest to hold=E2=80=94up f=
rom about 2.2% detailed in May. The other roughly quarter of the reserves a=
re held in a mix of corporate bonds, cash and small deposits.Here is the re=
port. Again it does=C2=A0not seem super-aggressive or anything, and you can=
 see where they=E2=80=99re coming from. Both Circle=E2=80=99s and Tether=E2=
=80=99s reports are light on detail, but I think that if you read them with=
 a reasonable amount of charity you will not come away thinking =E2=80=9Cth=
ese people are stretching wildly for yield, gambling their investors=E2=80=
=99 money on crazy assets.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re buying commercial paper=
, whatever, that is what you do with a pot of money that you want to be wor=
th $1. Still they have not always been great at=C2=A0saying that.
 =20
   =20
      Carbon structuring
   =20
 =20
If you have worked at an investment bank,  this story will feel very famili=
ar to you:The junior traders at TotalEnergies SE were essentially winging i=
t last September by orchestrating the French energy giant=E2=80=99s first s=
hipment of =E2=80=9Ccarbon-neutral=E2=80=9D natural gas. It=E2=80=99s the g=
reenest-possible designation for fossil fuel and an important step in makin=
g the company=E2=80=99s core product more palatable in a warming world. Nai=
ling down the deal involved googling and guesswork.Total had proposed the t=
rade after learning a client had already purchased two carbon-neutral cargo=
s from rivals at Royal Dutch Shell Plc, according to people with knowledge =
of the deal who asked not to be named discussing a private transaction. One=
 of these insiders said that only after getting the go-ahead did the inexpe=
rienced team attempt to figure out how to neutralize the emissions containe=
d in a hulking tanker full of liquified natural gas. Their first step was t=
o search the internet for worthy environmental projects that might offset t=
he pollution.I think that this nicely captures two fundamental elements of =
a complex trading business=C2=A0at an investment bank. (Or a commodity trad=
ing firm.)=C2=A0One is the combination of competitive pressures=C2=A0and, l=
ike, random googling. A client comes to you and says =E2=80=9Ca competitor =
will do X for us, what is your bid?=E2=80=9D And you go back to your boss a=
nd are like =E2=80=9CX? I have never even heard of X? But they=E2=80=99re t=
elling me Shell is doing it so we need to bid on it.=E2=80=9D And then you =
spend an hour on Wikipedia, take a stab at=C2=A0pricing, have an analyst pu=
t=C2=A0together a set of credentials pages saying that your bank is #1 in t=
he world on the X league table, and get on a call with the client that afte=
rnoon to talk smoothly and persuasively=C2=A0about how you are the only pos=
sible option for X and those amateurs at Shell could never pull off an X of=
 this complexity.But there=E2=80=99s another=C2=A0point here. Look, you=E2=
=80=99re a natural gas=C2=A0trader. Your basic training, as it were, covers=
 the fundamentals of gas markets and the economics of derivatives contracts=
. You know how much gas costs to get out of the ground and how much it cost=
s to ship. You understand why a client might want to buy or sell a cargo of=
 liquified natural gas at a given location for a given price. You understan=
d why the client might prefer the front-month futures or a later futures co=
ntract. There are basic relationships of economics and derivatives math inv=
olved here. The client wants to get the most stuff for the least money.And =
then a client comes to you and says =E2=80=9CI have some non-economic probl=
em that I want you to solve, but with gas.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=9Cnon-economi=
c=E2=80=9D is not always exactly right, but the client=E2=80=99s economics =
do not come from the gas contract itself. I used to work in a structured-tr=
ade-ish business at a bank, and the No. 1 and No. 2 problems that our clien=
ts wanted solved were (1) taxes and (2) accounting. =E2=80=9CWe want to giv=
e you some money for a trade that reduces our taxes=E2=80=9D would be a per=
fectly reasonable thing for the client to say, or =E2=80=9Cwe want to give =
you some money for a trade that increases our earnings per share.=E2=80=9D=
=C2=A0And then we=E2=80=99d build a trade for them, a trade built out of ta=
x and accounting knowledge. And if you just looked at it from a perspective=
 of=C2=A0derivatives math, you might say that they weren=E2=80=99t getting =
very much for their money. But then you might notice that their tax savings=
 were more than they paid us and be like =E2=80=9Cah, right, I see.=E2=80=
=9D=C2=A0Anyway the rest of this story is about how Total=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Ccarbon-neutral natural gas=E2=80=9D is fake:The resulting trade looks li=
ke a win for everyone. Total kept its promise to investors to shrink its ca=
rbon footprint. Impoverished communities received financial support. And th=
e buyer, China National Offshore Oil Corp., cited the shipment as one of th=
e steps it=E2=80=99s taking to =E2=80=9Cprovide green, clean energy to the =
nation.=E2=80=9D But climate experts and even a crucial organizer behind th=
e deal say it will do virtually nothing to decrease carbon dioxide in the a=
tmosphere, falling far short of neutral.=E2=80=9CThe claim that you can mar=
ket the sale of fossil fuels as carbon neutral because of a meager few doll=
ars you put into tropical conservation is not a defensible claim,=E2=80=9D =
says Danny Cullenward, a Stanford University lecturer and policy director a=
t CarbonPlan, a nonprofit group that analyzes climate solutions for impact.=
 =E2=80=A6The use of scientifically defined terms like =E2=80=9Ccarbon neut=
ral=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnet zero=E2=80=9D in marketing language introduce=
s additional confusion. Both terms mean balancing any emissions added to th=
e atmosphere with an equivalent amount of removal. Most experts agree that =
avoiding deforestation isn=E2=80=99t the same as removing greenhouse gases.=
 =E2=80=9CThis paradigm,=E2=80=9D warns Cullenward, =E2=80=9Cis encouraging=
 a fictitious engine that doesn=E2=80=99t help advance our net-zero goals.=
=E2=80=9DThat view isn=E2=80=99t reserved for outside critics. The leader o=
f South Pole, which helped develop the Zimbabwe project and sold its carbon=
 credits to Total, doesn=E2=80=99t believe forest protection can rectify po=
llution from natural gas. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s such obvious nonsense,=E2=
=80=9D says Renat Heuberger, co-founder of South Pole. =E2=80=9CEven my 9-y=
ear-old daughter will understand that=E2=80=99s not the case. You=E2=80=99r=
e burning fossil fuels and creating CO=E2=82=82 emissions.=E2=80=9DAnd, loo=
k, yes. Total=E2=80=99s gas trading is not going to solve climate change; i=
t is not even going to be carbon-neutral. But what are you comparing it to?=
 Total is in the business of sending natural gas to clients. That client wa=
nted natural gas. If the client had asked for natural gas and Total had sai=
d =E2=80=9Cthat is so bad for the environment, what if we just took a nice =
walk in the park instead and forgot about all this gas,=E2=80=9D the client=
 would have gone elsewhere.=C2=A0But that=E2=80=99s not what Total did, bec=
ause its junior traders are not in the business of saying no to client trad=
es. But they=C2=A0are=C2=A0in the business of structuring, of taking the bu=
ilding blocks of gas trades and putting them together to solve client probl=
ems, even client problems that are not of the form =E2=80=9CI need gas at t=
his location on this date.=E2=80=9D Total=E2=80=99s client had a problem of=
 the form =E2=80=9CI want to buy natural gas but I feel bad about it=E2=80=
=9D (or, realistically, =E2=80=9Cbut my shareholders will yell at me about =
being carbon-neutral,=E2=80=9D etc.), and Total=C2=A0went out and found som=
e people in Zimbabwe who did some forest-fire-prevention work in order to m=
ake the client feel better about the gas.=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s all a little st=
upid, sure, but it's how everything works. The point is that when I worked =
in finance a decade ago, the thing that you did was =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s =
use financial products to lower our clients=E2=80=99=C2=A0taxes.=E2=80=9D A=
nd now, the thing you do is =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s use financial products t=
o lower our clients=E2=80=99 emissions.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s strictly be=
tter! And in both cases there is a certain amount of fakery, but you iterat=
e, you get better. Some other trading firm will read this story and pitch c=
lients on a new form of carbon-neutral natural gas trade that is even carbo=
n-neutral-er than Total=E2=80=99s, which is apparently not a very high bar.=
 Lots of brainpower will be deployed toward the problem of reducing the env=
ironmental impact of natural gas,=C2=A0at banks and energy trading firms an=
d oil companies and utilities. Because there is a profitable trade there; y=
ou can get money and clients and a high spot in the league table if you fig=
ure out what it is.=C2=A0=C2=A0
 =20
   =20
      Fake opening bell
   =20
 =20
One important problem in a booming market for initial public offerings is t=
hat, in the U.S.,=C2=A0you can only have two companies ring the stock excha=
nge opening bell each day. (One at the New York Stock Exchange, one at Nasd=
aq.) So if 20 companies want to go public in a week, some of them will get =
bad bells. Like the closing bell:Exchanges typically ring their bells twice=
 a day, once to signal stocks can start changing hands and again to mark th=
e end of the trading day. Bell purists say the opening bell is best, though=
, as no executive wants to risk an awkward, forced-smile closing-bell ringi=
ng after a disappointing debut.Or the =E2=80=A6=C2=A0random bell that you c=
an just walk around with and ring sometime? I don=E2=80=99t know:The NYSE a=
nd Nasdaq, meanwhile, are scrambling to keep everyone happy, serving up con=
solation prizes to jilted bell ringers like a =E2=80=9Cfirst trade celebrat=
ion.=E2=80=9D For that celebration, stock market officials give a small gav=
el and a big bell to the company; the CEO or other officials ring it on the=
 trading floor after the first trade in the company=E2=80=99s stock.I=C2=A0=
do wonder at what point in the IPO process you start to think about this. I=
 imagine=C2=A0bankers at the initial IPO pitch=C2=A0saying =E2=80=9Cwe thin=
k you should go public next August, that's usually a quiet period for IPOs,=
 a lot of investors won=E2=80=99t be around and you won=E2=80=99t get a ver=
y good price but you have good odds of ringing the opening bell.=E2=80=9D
