5px;">Speaking of stablecoins</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the basic story of stablecoins=
. It is very useful, for people who trade crypto, to have a cryptocurrency =
worth $1. In many respects you live your life denominated in dollars, so yo=
u want a supply of dollars (as opposed to volatile assets like Bitcoin, etc=
.). But in many other respects you live your life=C2=A0<em>on the blockchai=
n</em>, so you want your money to be on the blockchain (as opposed to in a =
bank account in the U.S. payments system). A cryptocurrency worth a dollar =
solves both these problems: It is worth a dollar, but it can be traded on t=
he blockchain, transferred between crypto exchanges, held in a crypto walle=
t, and generally used as a cryptocurrency without interacting with the U.S.=
 banking system.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But how do you get a crypt=
ocurrency worth exactly $1? There are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/24713966.262444/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGl=
uaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTcvdGl0YW5pdW0tZ290LWNydXNoZWQ/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc10316d7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> some bad ways</a>, but there=E2=80=99s also a=C2=A0good simpl=
e way, which is that someone=C2=A0<em>else=C2=A0</em>interacts with the ban=
king system =E2=80=94=C2=A0by keeping dollars in the bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0an=
d issues a crypto token backed by those dollars, a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24713966.262444/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDEtMDkvYmxvY2tjaGFpbi1zdG9j=
ay1vZmZlcmluZ3MtYW5kLXN0YWJsZWNvaW5zLXdpbGwtZW5oYW5jZS1jcnlwdG8/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBcf5cee08" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">blockchain depositary receipt</a>=E2=80=9D on some dollars in=
 the bank. You give them a dollar, they give you back the token, and they p=
ut the dollar in the bank; you use the token on the blockchain as a cryptoc=
urrency; later, if you want, you give them back the token and they give you=
 back the dollar. That crypto token =E2=80=94=C2=A0a stablecoin =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is worth a dollar, so long as (1) you trust that person to actually k=
eep the money in the bank and (2) you trust the legal, contractual, persona=
l, etc. arrangements in which they promise to exchange the tokens back for =
dollars.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is the good simple way, but p=
roblems can creep in. One set of problems has to do with banks. Three probl=
ems with banks are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left:=
 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24713966.262444/aHR0cHM6L=
