mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  lend the money to your friend=
s</a>. Some stablecoins are affiliated with crypto exchanges or other crypt=
o-y businesses. Those businesses sometimes need financing. The stablecoin h=
as a huge pot of money. The affiliated business might come to the stablecoi=
n and say =E2=80=9Chey, lend us the money, we=E2=80=99ll pay it back with i=
nterest, we promise.=E2=80=9D And then the stablecoin will do that, because=
 the people running the stablecoin and the people running the affiliated bu=
siness are colleagues, or friends, or sometimes the same exact people. And =
then if the affiliated business loses money then, oops, your=C2=A0customers=
 will be mad.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You could just steal=
 the money, why not.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The combination =
of all of these factors means that it would honestly be kind of surprising =
for a stablecoin to actually be backed by a pot of money in a bank account.=
 On the other hand, =E2=80=9Cwe are backed by a bunch of dollars in a bank =
account=E2=80=9D is a very pleasant thing for a stablecoin to=C2=A0<em>say<=
/em>, because it sounds so simple and so safe. And, you know, lightly-to-no=
t-at-all-regulated business. So =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh ... you could just say it=
?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/24713966.262444/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2F=
