om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Carbon structuring</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you have worked at an investment ba=
nk, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24713966.26244=
4/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjEtMDgtMTEvdGhlL=
WZpY3RpdGlvdXMtd29ybGQtb2YtY2FyYm9uLW5ldXRyYWwtZm9zc2lsLWZ1ZWw/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB42fb49e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> this story</a> will feel very familiar to you:</p><blockquote=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The junior traders at TotalEnergies SE were e=
ssentially winging it last September by orchestrating the French energy gia=
nt=E2=80=99s first shipment of =E2=80=9Ccarbon-neutral=E2=80=9D natural gas=
. It=E2=80=99s the greenest-possible designation for fossil fuel and an imp=
ortant step in making the company=E2=80=99s core product more palatable in =
a warming world. Nailing down the deal involved googling and guesswork.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Total had proposed the trade after learning a =
client had already purchased two carbon-neutral cargos from rivals at Royal=
 Dutch Shell Plc, according to people with knowledge of the deal who asked =
not to be named discussing a private transaction. One of these insiders sai=
d that only after getting the go-ahead did the inexperienced team attempt t=
o figure out how to neutralize the emissions contained in a hulking tanker =
full of liquified natural gas. Their first step was to search the internet =
for worthy environmental projects that might offset the pollution.</p></blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that this nicely captures two =
fundamental elements of a complex trading business=C2=A0at an investment ba=
nk. (Or a commodity trading firm.)=C2=A0One is the combination of competiti=
ve pressures=C2=A0and, like, random googling. A client comes to you and say=
s =E2=80=9Ca competitor will do X for us, what is your bid?=E2=80=9D And yo=
u go back to your boss and are like =E2=80=9CX? I have never even heard of =
X? But they=E2=80=99re telling me Shell is doing it so we need to bid on it=
.=E2=80=9D And then you spend an hour on Wikipedia, take a stab at=C2=A0pri=
cing, have an analyst put=C2=A0together a set of credentials pages saying t=
hat your bank is #1 in the world on the X league table, and get on a call w=
ith the client that afternoon to talk smoothly and persuasively=C2=A0about =
how you are the only possible option for X and those amateurs at Shell coul=
d never pull off an X of this complexity.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">B=
ut there=E2=80=99s another=C2=A0point here. Look, you=E2=80=99re a natural =
gas=C2=A0trader. Your basic training, as it were, covers the fundamentals o=
f gas markets and the economics of derivatives contracts. You know how much=
 gas costs to get out of the ground and how much it costs to ship. You unde=
rstand why a client might want to buy or sell a cargo of liquified natural =
gas at a given location for a given price. You understand why the client mi=
ght prefer the front-month futures or a later futures contract. There are b=
asic relationships of economics and derivatives math involved here. The cli=
ent wants to get the most stuff for the least money.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">And then a client comes to you and says =E2=80=9CI have some non-=
economic problem that I want you to solve, but with gas.=E2=80=9D Or =E2=80=
=9Cnon-economic=E2=80=9D is not always exactly right, but the client=E2=80=
=99s economics do not come from the gas contract itself. I used to work in =
a structured-trade-ish business at a bank, and the No. 1 and No. 2 problems=
 that our clients wanted solved were (1) taxes and (2) accounting. =E2=80=
=9CWe want to give you some money for a trade that reduces our taxes=E2=80=
=9D would be a perfectly reasonable thing for the client to say, or =E2=80=
=9Cwe want to give you some money for a trade that increases our earnings p=
er share.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then we=E2=80=
=99d build a trade for them, a trade built out of tax and accounting knowle=
dge. And if you just looked at it from a perspective of=C2=A0derivatives ma=
th, you might say that they weren=E2=80=99t getting very much for their mon=
ey. But then you might notice that their tax savings were more than they pa=
id us and be like =E2=80=9Cah, right, I see.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the rest of this story is about how Total=E2=80=99s=
 =E2=80=9Ccarbon-neutral natural gas=E2=80=9D is fake:</p><blockquote><p st=
yle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The resulting trade looks like a win for everyone. =
Total kept its promise to investors to shrink its carbon footprint. Impover=
ished communities received financial support. And the buyer, China National=
 Offshore Oil Corp., cited the shipment as one of the steps it=E2=80=99s ta=
king to =E2=80=9Cprovide green, clean energy to the nation.=E2=80=9D But cl=
imate experts and even a crucial organizer behind the deal say it will do v=
irtually nothing to decrease carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, falling far =
short of neutral.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe claim that y=
ou can market the sale of fossil fuels as carbon neutral because of a meage=
r few dollars you put into tropical conservation is not a defensible claim,=
=E2=80=9D says Danny Cullenward, a Stanford University lecturer and policy =
director at CarbonPlan, a nonprofit group that analyzes climate solutions f=
or impact. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The use of scientifica=
lly defined terms like =E2=80=9Ccarbon neutral=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cnet ze=
ro=E2=80=9D in marketing language introduces additional confusion. Both ter=
ms mean balancing any emissions added to the atmosphere with an equivalent =
amount of removal. Most experts agree that avoiding deforestation isn=E2=80=
=99t the same as removing greenhouse gases. =E2=80=9CThis paradigm,=E2=80=
=9D warns Cullenward, =E2=80=9Cis encouraging a fictitious engine that does=
n=E2=80=99t help advance our net-zero goals.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">That view isn=E2=80=99t reserved for outside critics. The leader=
 of South Pole, which helped develop the Zimbabwe project and sold its carb=
on credits to Total, doesn=E2=80=99t believe forest protection can rectify =
pollution from natural gas. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s such obvious nonsense,=E2=
=80=9D says Renat Heuberger, co-founder of South Pole. =E2=80=9CEven my 9-y=
ear-old daughter will understand that=E2=80=99s not the case. You=E2=80=99r=
e burning fossil fuels and creating CO=E2=82=82 emissions.=E2=80=9D</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And, look, yes. Total=E2=80=99s gas t=
rading is not going to solve climate change; it is not even going to be car=
bon-neutral. But what are you comparing it to? Total is in the business of =
sending natural gas to clients. That client wanted natural gas. If the clie=
nt had asked for natural gas and Total had said =E2=80=9Cthat is so bad for=
 the environment, what if we just took a nice walk in the park instead and =
forgot about all this gas,=E2=80=9D the client would have gone elsewhere.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that=E2=80=99s not what Total di=
d, because its junior traders are not in the business of saying no to clien=
t trades. But they=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>in the business of structuring, o=
f taking the building blocks of gas trades and putting them together to sol=
ve client problems, even client problems that are not of the form =E2=80=9C=
I need gas at this location on this date.=E2=80=9D Total=E2=80=99s client h=
ad a problem of the form =E2=80=9CI want to buy natural gas but I feel bad =
about it=E2=80=9D (or, realistically, =E2=80=9Cbut my shareholders will yel=
l at me about being carbon-neutral,=E2=80=9D etc.), and Total=C2=A0went out=
 and found some people in Zimbabwe who did some forest-fire-prevention work=
 in order to make the client feel better about the gas.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s all a little stupid, sure, but it's how e=
verything works. The point is that when I worked in finance a decade ago, t=
he thing that you did was =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s use financial products to =
lower our clients=E2=80=99=C2=A0taxes.=E2=80=9D And now, the thing you do i=
s =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s use financial products to lower our clients=E2=80=
=99 emissions.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s strictly better! And in both cases t=
here is a certain amount of fakery, but you iterate, you get better. Some o=
ther trading firm will read this story and pitch clients on a new form of c=
arbon-neutral natural gas trade that is even carbon-neutral-er than Total=
=E2=80=99s, which is apparently not a very high bar. Lots of brainpower wil=
l be deployed toward the problem of reducing the environmental impact of na=
tural gas,=C2=A0at banks and energy trading firms and oil companies and uti=
lities. Because there is a profitable trade there; you can get money and cl=
ients and a high spot in the league table if you figure out what it is.=C2=
=A0=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacin=
g=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
